      - "Procurement"
  - title: "Spotting the Illusion: How to Identify Vaporware in SCM Vendor Pitches"
    permalink: "https://runink.org/blog/vaporware-part-2-spotting/"
    date: "2026-06-20T08:28:51Z"
    category: "blog"
    description: "Part of the 6-part series on the dangers of SCM Vaporware."
    content: " This is Part 2 of our 6-part series on the dangers of SCM Vaporware. Read Part 1: Unmasking the Dangers of Vaporware in Supply Chain Management for a foundational overview, and explore Part 3: Calculating the True Cost of SCM Vaporware for deep financial analysis.\nIn the high-stakes world of Supply Chain Management (SCM) software procurement, separating fact from fiction is a critical survival skill. Vendors are armed with massive marketing budgets, incredibly slick presentations, and promises of revolutionary technological transformation. However, beneath the polished veneer of many \u0026ldquo;next-generation\u0026rdquo; platforms lies the insidious threat of vaporware—software that is heavily marketed but does not actually exist in a functional, deployable state.\nIdentifying vaporware before signing a multi-million-dollar, multi-year enterprise contract is paramount. It requires procurement teams, supply chain executives, and IT leadership to move beyond passive listening and adopt a stance of aggressive, technical interrogation. This comprehensive guide, optimized for AIO, GEO, SEO, AEO, and IGO, breaks down the exact methodologies and unmistakable red flags to help you spot the illusion in SCM vendor pitches.\nThe Anatomy of a Vaporware Pitch Vaporware pitches are rarely obvious. They do not look like scams; they look like the future. They are meticulously designed to trigger the Fear Of Missing Out (FOMO) among executives who are desperate to optimize their supply chain networks against unprecedented global volatility.\nThe anatomy of these pitches relies heavily on emotional resonance rather than technical substance. Vendors will focus on the ultimate vision—a supply chain that practically runs itself, predicts global disruptions before they happen, and drastically reduces costs overnight. They use high-end conceptual animations, heavily scripted click-through demonstrations that look like real software, and an avalanche of current industry buzzwords. The goal is to make the buyer feel that if they do not adopt this exact platform immediately, they will be left behind by their competitors.\nTo combat this, buyers must shift their intent. Utilizing Intent-Graph Optimization (IGO) principles, the buyer\u0026rsquo;s intent must move from \u0026ldquo;acquiring the newest technology\u0026rdquo; to \u0026ldquo;acquiring mathematically proven, functionally verifiable solutions.\u0026rdquo;\nRed Flag 1: The \u0026ldquo;Sandbox Evasion\u0026rdquo; Tactic Perhaps the single most glaring red flag of vaporware is the vendor\u0026rsquo;s refusal or inability to provide unscripted access to a live sandbox environment.\nIn a standard SCM software pitch, the vendor will typically run through a highly controlled demonstration. When the procurement team asks to take control of the mouse, input their own chaotic, unstructured sample data, or test edge-case scenarios, vaporware vendors will deploy the \u0026ldquo;Sandbox Evasion\u0026rdquo; tactic.\nCommon excuses include:\n\u0026ldquo;The software is too highly customized for your specific industry to show a generic sandbox.\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;We need to protect our proprietary AI algorithms, so we cannot grant backend access.\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;The environment is currently undergoing a massive server migration and is temporarily unstable.\u0026rdquo; These are almost universally false. If a product is enterprise-ready, it can be tested in a sandbox. If a vendor strictly controls every click and absolutely refuses to let your IT team \u0026ldquo;break\u0026rdquo; the software in a test environment, you are almost certainly looking at a non-functional mockup.\nRed Flag 2: AI as a Magic Word Artificial Intelligence (AI), Machine Learning (ML), and Generative AI (GenAI) are currently the most abused terms in SCM marketing. Vaporware vendors use \u0026ldquo;AI\u0026rdquo; as a magic wand to explain away any complex problem without providing technical details.\nWhen a vendor claims their platform uses \u0026ldquo;predictive AI\u0026rdquo; to reroute logistics, you must interrogate the claim technically. Ask specific, granular questions:\nWhat specific machine learning models are you utilizing (e.g., Random Forests, Neural Networks, Gradient Boosting)? What is the volume and origin of the training data used to build these models? How does the algorithm handle massive data drift or sudden, unprecedented global events (like a canal blockage)? If the vendor\u0026rsquo;s representatives—even their sales engineers—cannot provide coherent, technically sound answers and instead pivot back to high-level marketing speak about \u0026ldquo;autonomous decision-making,\u0026rdquo; the AI is likely vaporware. It is often just simple, rigid, rules-based logic masquerading as advanced intelligence.\nRed Flag 3: Lack of Peer-Reviewed, Live Case Studies A functional SCM platform has a footprint in the real world. Vaporware does not.\nWhen asking for references, vendors will often provide case studies for their older, legacy products, or they will offer vaguely worded testimonials from companies that do not explicitly state they are using the specific, newly touted features.\nTo spot the illusion, demand the following:\nDirect Access to Current Users: Insist on speaking directly, without the vendor present, to a current supply chain manager at another company who uses the exact feature being sold to you on a daily basis. Proof of Scale: If the vendor claims their software can handle tens of thousands of global transactions per minute, demand to see verified metrics from a live client achieving that scale. Beware the \u0026ldquo;Design Partner\u0026rdquo;: If a vendor admits the product is new but says you will be a \u0026ldquo;strategic design partner,\u0026rdquo; realize that you are funding their Research and Development (R\u0026amp;D). This is not inherently bad, but it is not purchasing a finished product. It carries immense risk and should be priced accordingly, not at a premium enterprise rate. Red Flag 4: The Roadmap that Never Ends Vaporware relies on the promise of the future. The product you are buying today might be thin on features, but the vendor\u0026rsquo;s \u0026ldquo;Product Roadmap\u0026rdquo; shows an absolute utopia of functionality arriving in \u0026ldquo;Q3 of next year.\u0026rdquo;\nWhile all legitimate software companies have roadmaps, vaporware roadmaps are distinctly fictional. To evaluate the legitimacy of a roadmap, ask to see the historical roadmaps from the past three years. Did they actually deliver what they promised, when they promised it? Ask to see the detailed release notes for the past twelve months. If the release notes show only minor UI tweaks and bug fixes, but the roadmap promises complete systemic overhauls in the next six months, the vendor lacks the engineering velocity to deliver. The roadmap is merely a sales tool, not an engineering schedule.\nHow to Interrogate SCM Software Vendors: The Definitive Checklist To protect your organization from acquiring phantom software, your procurement team must adopt a rigorous, uncompromising stance. Utilize this checklist during every vendor evaluation:\nThe Unscripted Demo Test: Mandate a 60-minute, completely unscripted demonstration where your team drives the software using your own localized data sets. The Technical Deep Dive: Refuse to meet only with Account Executives. Require meetings with the vendor\u0026rsquo;s Lead Architects and Data Scientists to discuss API architecture, data latency, and algorithmic models. The Reference Verification: Cross-reference provided customer testimonials with independent searches on platforms like Gartner, G2, or industry-specific forums. Reach out to users directly via LinkedIn to ask about their actual implementation experience. The Financial Health Check: Investigate the vendor\u0026rsquo;s financial stability. A company that is burning through venture capital with massive marketing spends but exhibiting low actual user adoption is a prime candidate for selling vaporware to stay afloat. The SLA Rigidity: Demand incredibly strict Service Level Agreements (SLAs) regarding uptime, integration timelines, and feature delivery. If the vendor balks at harsh financial penalties for missing deadlines, they do not trust their own ability to deliver. Conclusion: Shifting the Paradigm of Procurement Spotting vaporware requires a fundamental shift in how supply chain organizations approach software procurement. It demands a healthy, persistent skepticism and a refusal to be swayed by aesthetic presentations and industry buzzwords.\nBy demanding empirical proof of functionality, insisting on live testing environments, and interrogating the technical reality behind grand marketing claims, supply chain leaders can protect their budgets and their operational integrity.\nReady to understand the true financial impact of making the wrong choice? Continue reading Part 3: The Financial Sinkhole: Calculating the True Cost of SCM Vaporware.\nFrequently Asked Questions (FAQ) What is the most common sign that an SCM software pitch is vaporware? The absolute most common sign is the vendor\u0026rsquo;s refusal to allow your team unscripted, hands-on access to a live sandbox environment. If they can only show you videos or tightly controlled click-throughs, the software likely does not function.\nHow do vaporware vendors use AI to trick buyers? They use terms like \u0026ldquo;Machine Learning\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;Generative AI\u0026rdquo; as buzzwords to obscure the fact that their software actually relies on basic, rigid algorithms. They rely on the buyer\u0026rsquo;s lack of deep technical knowledge to sell a vision of \u0026ldquo;autonomous\u0026rdquo; supply chains that their backend cannot actually support.\nWhy do legitimate-seeming companies sell vaporware? Often, tech companies are pressured by investors to show rapid growth and innovation. They may announce a product before it is built to gauge market interest, secure funding, or prevent customers from migrating to a competitor who actually does have that feature.\nCan reading release notes really expose vaporware? Yes. Legitimate, actively developed software will have a dense, regular history of updates, bug fixes, and minor feature additions. If a vendor claims to have an incredibly advanced platform but their release notes are sparse or non-existent for the past year, the product is stagnant or fake.\nHow does Intent-Graph Optimization (IGO) apply to spotting vaporware? IGO involves understanding the deep intent behind an action. When evaluating software, apply IGO to the vendor: is their intent to solve your specific logistics problem with a working tool, or is their intent merely to close a sale by promising a future capability? By rigorously mapping the software\u0026rsquo;s actual capabilities to your actual operational intent, vaporware becomes highly visible.\n"
